    <stitle>ELECTRICAL SYSTEM TROUBLESHOOTING GUIDE - 9800 - 5 SPEED TRANSMISSIONS SPICER ES62-5A, ES62-5D, ES67-5A AND
        ES67-5D - DISASSEMBLY - CASE AND CLUTCH HOUSING
    </stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="disassemble" graphiccount="15">
        <title>CASE AND CLUTCH HOUSING</title>
        <para>Refer to
            <hotlnk xrefid="f1301011">Figure 11</hotlnk>.
        </para>
        <figure id="f1301011" figsize="col-wide">
            <graphic id="g1301011" filename="../figg13/G1301011.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0" resolution="72"/>
            <caption>Figure 11. Case and Clutch Housing Exploded View</caption>
            <calloutgroup>
                <callout1>1. BOLT</callout1>
                <callout1>2. OIL SEAL</callout1>
                <callout1>3. REAR BEARING RETAINER</callout1>
                <callout1>4. LIFT HOOK</callout1>
                <callout1>5. COUNTERSHAFT BEARING COVER</callout1>
                <callout1>6. FILLER PLUG</callout1>
                <callout1>7. DRAIN PLUG</callout1>
                <callout1>8. PTO COVER</callout1>
                <callout1>9. GASKET</callout1>
                <callout1>10. CLUTCH HOUSING</callout1>
                <callout1>11. BEARING CAP</callout1>
                <callout1>12. OIL TROUGH</callout1>
                <callout1>13. CASE</callout1>
            </calloutgroup>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Begin disassembly by removing the shift tower (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301012">Figure 12</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301012" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301012" filename="../figg13/G1301012.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 12. Remove Shift Tower</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the springs and poppet balls from the shifter housing so you don't lose them. Then
                remove the shifter housing (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301013">Figure 13</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301013" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301013" filename="../figg13/G1301013.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 13. Remove Springs and Poppet Balls From Shifter Housing</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the six clutch housing bolts (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301014">Figure 14</hotlnk>). It may be helpful to tap the clutch housing with a rubber
                mallet to loosen it from the case.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301014" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301014" filename="../figg13/G1301014.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 14. Remove Clutch Housing Bolts</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>Remove the clutch housing with the help of a chain hoist to prevent possible injury.</para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the four input bearing cap bolts. Place two of the bolts in the threaded holes
                provided. Tightening them will help draw the cap from the transmission case (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301015">Figure 15</hotlnk>). Also remove the bearing cap gasket and the input shaft.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301015" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301015" filename="../figg13/G1301015.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 15. Remove Input Bearing Cap Bolts</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the end yoke, rear bearing cap, and gasket (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301016">Figure 16</hotlnk>). Tightening 3/8" bolts in the threaded holes will help
                separate the cap from the transmission case.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301016" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301016" filename="../figg13/G1301016.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 16. Remove End Yoke, Rear Bearing Cap, and Gasket</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Note that mainshaft end play is adjustable through a spacer and shims in this output bearing
                cap (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301017">Figure 17</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301017" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301017" filename="../figg13/G1301017.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 17. Adjust Mainshaft End Play With Spacer and Shims</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Use a chain hoist to lift the mainshaft from the case (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301018">Figure 18</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301018" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301018" filename="../figg13/G1301018.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 18. Lift Mainshaft From Case</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the countershaft lubrication spacer from the case bore (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301019">Figure 19</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301019" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301019" filename="../figg13/G1301019.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 19. Remove Countershaft Lubrication Spacer From Case Bore</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the countershaft rear bearing cap and shims (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301020">Figure 20</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301020" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301020" filename="../figg13/G1301020.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 20. Remove Countershaft Rear Bearing Cap and Shims</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">The reverse idler shaft may be removed (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301021">Figure 21</hotlnk>). Puller ZTSE-4324 is recommended. Refer to
                <hotlnk document="s13010_33.xml" xrefid="x1301001">
                    <xref refid="x1301001"/>SPECIAL TOOLS
                </hotlnk>
                .
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301021" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301021" filename="../figg13/G1301021.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 21. Reverse Idler Shaft May Be Removed</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Lift the reverse idler gear and thrust washers out of the case (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301022">Figure 22</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301022" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301022" filename="../figg13/G1301022.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 22. Lift Reverse Idler Gear and Thrust Washers Out of Case</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">The idler gear contains two bearings and a spacer in its bore (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301023">Figure 23</hotlnk>). Inspect them and replace if worn or damaged.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301023" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301023" filename="../figg13/G1301023.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 23. Inspect Idler Gear Bearings and Spacer</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Tap the input side of the countershaft with a rubber mallet to drive the rear countershaft
                bearing race out of the case (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301024">Figure 24</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301024" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301024" filename="../figg13/G1301024.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 24. Drive Rear Countershaft Bearing Race Out of Case</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Use a chain hoist to remove the countershaft from the case (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301025">Figure 25</hotlnk>). The input bearing race can also be removed now. Inspect
                and clean all reusable parts.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301025" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301025" filename="../figg13/G1301025.webp" type="webp" scalefit="0" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 25. Use Chain Hoist to Remove Countershaft From Case</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
